<qandaset defaultlabel=qanda id=java>

<title>Java Frequently Asked Questions</title>

<qandaentry>
<question>
<para>Where are the Java debian packges?</para>
</question>
<answer>
<para>
Amend <filename>/etc/apt/sources.list</filename> to include 
<programlisting>
# Java
deb http://debian.innovationsw.com/debian unstable/i386/
</programlisting>
</para>
</answer>
</qandaentry>

<qandaentry>
<question>
<para>
What packages are available?
</para>
</question>
<answer>
<para>
The minimum list of packages I use is:
<screen>
# dpkg -l | grep -i java
ii  ant            1.6.2-2        Java based build tool like make
ii  freemind       0.7.1-3        A Java Program for creating and viewing Mind
ii  java-common    0.22           Base of all Java packages
ii  java-virtual-m 0.3            Dummy Java virtual machine
ii  java2-common   1              Common facilities for all Java2 environments
ii  junit          3.8.1.1-2      Automated testing framework for Java
ii  libant1.6-java 1.6.2-2        Java based build tool like make -- library
ii  libjaxp1.2-jav 1.2.01-1       Java XML parser and transformer APIs (DOM, S
ii  libxerces2-jav 2.6.2-1        Validating XML parser for Java with DOM leve
</screen>
Start with <filename>java-virtual-machine-dummy</filename>, then <filename>ant</filename>.
</para>
</answer>
</qandaentry>

<qandaentry>
<question>
<para>What other utilities do I need?</para>
</question>
<answer>
<para>
I love the IzPack for installation. 
Get it from 
<ulink url="http://www.izforge.com/izpack">
    <citetitle>http://www.izforge.com/izpack</citetitle>
</ulink>.
Installing IzPack is as easy as:
<screen>
    java -jar IzPack-install.jar
</screen>
</para>
</answer>
</qandaentry>

